Proteins belonging to the heat shock protein (HSP) family are well known for their roles as chaperons in protein folding. These proteins have been observed to play similar roles in the maintenance of proper viral protein folding and stabilization (
 Seo et al., 2018). In many viral infections, viruses commandeer vital cellular components, leading to cellular stress. Cellular stress is often represented as unfolded protein response (UPR) in cells (
 Geller et al., 2012; 
 Wang et al., 2018). Previous studies have reported that ORF3 and ORF2 of the virus induce UPR and ER stress (
 Surjit et al., 2007; 
 John et al., 2011; 
 Xu et al., 2014). In our study, we found enrichment of proteins related to processing in the endoplasmic reticulum, and UPR further confirms the dependence of HEV on the host ER machinery.
